this is probably the only 5-star restaurant that i am dying to eat at again, and again and again :) everything on the menu had so many flavor explosions. it was a party in my mouth. the service was excellent (of course) and they were very accommodating. the cheese tray, apps, main course, dessert and wine were all superb. these dishes were my favs of the night and still make me *drool* just thinking about them -- (1) Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar, Zucchini Pearls and Lettuce Cream, (2) Mushroom Dusted Sea Scallops with English Pea Purée, Shimeji Mushrooms and Meyer Lemon, (3) Warm Louisiana Butter Cake with Huckleberry Compote and Vanilla Ice Cream ...the cheese tray was also really tasty, but i can't seem to find the card with the names :( the thing that makes gary danko better than any other 5-star restaurant is that the food has character, not sure if that make sense. i've eaten at per se and other fancy places, but never crave to really go back and have another meal there (and spend that much money) ....but i would definitely go back to danko's!

In a nutshell: Decorative decor, warm ambiance, helpful and professional staff, and, oh yes, great food! In detail: Let's just go straight for the food, shall we? Everyone at my table ordered 5 courses, so of course, I did as well. 5 courses for $89...that's a "bargain!" But hey, you only live once. Anyway, yes, the food. If I can recall, here's what I ordered: Lobster Salad with Summer Melons Sweet White Corn Soup with Corn Truffle Ravioli Pancetta Wrapped Frog Legs Guinea Hen Breast and Boudin with Saffron Paella Rice, Chorizo, and Clam Ragout Baked Chocolate Souffle with Two Sauces The lobster salad was excellent. The lobster pieces were meaty and mouth-watering, while the melons were a good compliment to the dish. The sweet corn soup was excellent as well. The waiter first brought out a soup bowl with nothing but the corn truffle ravioli in the middle of it. It made me wonder, "Ummm...I could've sworn I ordered soup and not one piece of ravioli." But then he whipped out a miniature pot and in that pot was the corn soup. He poured it over the ravioli and for me, the rest...was heaven. The pancetta ("bacon") wrapped frog legs were very tasty. Frog legs taste like chicken. Everyone knows that. But whenever you wrap something up in pancetta ("bacon"), it always tastes good...ALWAYS! The hen breast was a disappointment for me. It lacked flavor. The fatty skin tasted good, but everything else lacked punch. The rice was a bit mushy and the boudin (first time I've eaten it) was something I'd rather not eat again. This course was the only lowlight of the dinner for me. The chocolate souffle was decadent. The two sauces were creme en glaze sauce...and I forgot the other. My only complaint about the souffle was that my souffle was rather mushy in the middle, as if it wasn't baked thoroughly enough. I can lay blame on the sauces, but I'm not so sure if the sauces made my souffle mushy. When you eat souffles, you expect it to be fluffy all the way through. My dining experience here was phenomenal! Even though there were a couple of small things that I didn't enjoy quite as much, they didn't sway my decision enough to make me rate this place below 5 stars.

I must confess - my meal on 12/1/09 at Gary Danko is - to date - the best meal of my life. It has totally reset my conception of food and fine dining...and in many ways has raised the proverbial bar for me as far as my yelp reviews. There are already over a thousand glowing reviews of Chef Danko & his restaurant...so you don't need me to tell you it's good...and honestly I've struggled for 3 days just trying to conceive of the words that I would use to describe this experience and actually do it justice. This restaurant was highly recommended to us by a family member, and (to be honest) we were skeptical that any meal or dining experience could really justify this type of price tag. Upon stepping into the restaurant - we were warmly greeted, whisked away to our cozy table, and our waiter made his way to us quickly with menus and other relevant info. The man and I had done some research - so we had a good idea of what we wanted to try - and we were able to place our full order quickly. I chose the Autumn Tasting Menu with wine pairings and the man had 4 courses with tailored wine pairing as well. As the amuse bouche arrived and then our first glass of wine...we quickly began to see that we were in for more than simply a meal...more than just great service...we were in for a guided tour of our sense of taste...an introspective exploration of our palates. The skepticism quickly faded... One thing I cannot say enough about is my appetizer - the Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar, Salsify and Lettuce Cream. These delectable oysters are haunting my every thought! The glaze...the lettuce cream...so inappropriate - but my goodness I could have that as a cup of soup! I've had oysters and fresh from the Gulf Coast...I'd always thought they were good but they were kind of something i could live without...I'm pretty sure that's changed. This appetizer perfectly communicates to you the essence of oyster and why it is something you should never live without. I could write pages about every dish and wine, but I will spare you. However, our stars for the night were the previous mentioned oysters, Risotto with Lobster, Quail Stuffed with Foie Gras, Mushrooms and Quinoa, Yams, Salsify and Pomegranate, cheese cart, and the Warm Louisiana Butter Cake with Caramelized Apples, Huckleberry Compote and Vanilla Ice Cream. Our review research led us to these choices, and we're so glad it did!! Rounding out our other choices: Horseradish Crusted Salmon Medallion with Dilled Cucumbers and Mustard Sauce, Coconut Thai Curry with Lemongrass, Calamari, Lobster, Scallions and Shitake Mushrooms (wow the most tender and perfectly cooked calamari I've ever tasted), Seared Filet of Beef with Spaetzle, Butternut Squash, Crimini Mushrooms, Bone Marrow Butter and Shallot Marmalade (wow bone marrow butter and shallot marmalade - again delicious), Baked Chocolate Soufflé with Two Sauces. All of these dishes were fantastic and shined in their own right. As I have mentioned in other reviews, I notice the little details when it comes to service. Let me tell you - the service at this restaurant is on a whole other level. These folks are so on top of their game and observant - you could almost swear that they read minds. You never seem to be waiting or wanting for anything...you are either being given the perfect amount of info on your next wine...having your just finished dish whisked away...having your water refilled and you didn't even notice...and before you even knew you were waiting on your next course it's there and the joy of taste starts all over again. We asked our waiter about mid meal if he could write down the man's wine pairings so we could reference them later. Our waiter graciously did this for us AND included a copy of the Tasting Menu which he had Chef Danko sign for us. This was waiting for us at the maître d' stand on beautiful restaurant stationary tucked away in a lovely gold envelope. This was the perfect souvenir for our honeymoon trip to San Francisco and our visit to Gary Danko. Our final resolution is not only that the price is beyond fair for the meal and the experience...but that it's a MUST DO. Maybe some budgets cannot allow every week, but it is definitely a must do at least once and as often as you can.

5 courses. Every one a star. I'd give it six if I could, because this place negates every five star I've ever handed out. Probably the best meal I've ever had. No shit. You feel blessed afterwards. 'Nuff said. Seriously.

Some showed up more often than others and I noticed that each person had a specific task that they do for every table. Because we were in the corner. the waiters didn't serve our plates at the same time as other reviews had mentioned. I did see them do it for parties of 4, where the table was located in the center.

It's all been said before! Five stars YES (for outstanding service, blousy flowers, sexy atmosphere, cocktails, wine, and lovely lovely food).

This place is totally worth calling them 2 months ahead (to the day!) for my hubby's bday dinner. I swear, my only regret of the night is that we should have gone here instead of Masa's for our anniversary a couple months ago. Their 5 courses was was far superior to Masa's 9-course experience - The food tasted better (some orgasmic moments), their servings were much larger (I was super-stuffed at the end of the 5 courses, while still hungry at the end of the 9 courses), the wine pours more generous, and the service impeccable. Since I was driving, I let my hubby have the wine pairing (after all, it was his day), while I just ordered wine by the glass. Amuse-bouche - creamy green soup (I think the server said zucchini?). Very warm and yummy, perfect thing to get us started. We both got glasses of champagne which were just perfectly chilled, crisp, and dry. 1st course - I got the Glazed Oysters w/ Osetra caviar, and man they really don't skimp on the caviar! And this is considering they charge $95/ounce for it if you order the caviar service. Tasted heavenly, a great start for the night. Hubby got a nice-sized portion of seared foie gras (unlike some restaurants that give you a little tiny sliver). I was still drinking my champagne while hubby got a sweet dessert wine (Tokai). 2nd course - I got the foie gras...this time an even larger portion than what my hubby got for his first course (mwahahahha!) since I got it as an entree (why get fish when you can get foie gras!). If I wasn't set on trying some of the oysters w/ caviar I might have gotten 2 courses of this stuff, it's sooo damn good! :) Hubby got seared sea scallops...it was super-good, just so buttery and perfectly cooked...prob the best sea scallops I've ever had (and I don't normally eat the stuff). I'll still take my super-sized portion of foie gras over it though. A nice light white wine came w/ my hubby's scallops, while I still extended my champagne from the beginning and finished off the last couple sips of my hubby's (hey, he got the full pairing anyway). 3rd course - I got quail stuffed w/ foie gras (can you tell I was craving foie gras?). It was great, but my prize for best preparation of quail (or any poultry for that matter) still goes to Fleur de Lys for their quail stuffed w/ veal sweetbreads. They give a much bigger portion here though I still thought it was very good, better than my hubby's beef tenderloin...I think in the future, we should prob just avoid steaks at french restaurants, since you an get good steaks anyway, but the quail I got can only be gotten at fancy french places. Since I asked them to pick my glass of wine for me, they gave me a nice light-to-medium bodied spanish rioja. The server overpoured a little bit, and she was like "oops" and smiled at me. I saw there was a little bit left over and the bottle and asked her if she can let me have it and she let me (yay!) and joked to not tell her boss. Hubby's wine pairing (a big heavy red for his steak) looked teeny tiny compared to my supersized serving of wine! Whee! Cheese course - I gotta say, the cheese cart was extremely impressive. I only wish I wasn't already kinda stuffed from the previous courses, then maybe I would have enjoyed it more. All the cheeses I got (even the stinky ones) were excellent. Hubby got this strong red wine that seemed very port-like in strength, but none of the sweetness...went really well w/ all the cheeses. I'm still grateful for my extra-large pour for my quail so I actually still had wine left over for my cheese course! Yay! Dessert - I got the chocolate souffle, hubby got grand marnier souffle. They were both yummy, and again, a much larger portion than what I expected for a 5-course meal. The server (different one this time) started pouring my hubby's wine pairing and saying it would go great w/ his chocolate souffle, but then I said that my hubby was actually getting the grand marnier. He shrugged and said playfully that maybe he should just drink it, then gave it to me since I was getting the chocolate. More free booze! I'm loving this place. Good thing it took us over 3 hours to eat so I can digest all the freebie alcohol :) After dessert, my hubby got a nice plate w/ a bunch of candies/goodies on it and it said happy birthday and had a candle. We were so stuffed at this point, but I couldn't resist a few bites of the goodies! :) I first told them about this a couple months ago so they had great attention to detail. The service was also just so warm and friendly, which was very different from other restaurants of this caliber. At the Ritz, they treated us like royalty, at Gary Danko, they treated us like their best friend. I gotta say this definitely one of the top meals I've had in the city...sure, I've had more spectacular meals, but those cost way more $$$! Especially since this place is more affordable (esp if you get a 3-course), I will definitely come back!

Hands down, our favorite restaurant in the city. Ain't much more to add about the food so we'll spare the gory details. We'd just like to inform all of you in Yelp-land of the subtler details of Mr. Danko's fine establishment: - The paradox of Danko, it's a great value considering it's high-end cuisine. You ain't gonna find a much better deal for a multi-course meal with this level of service, ambience, and snob-appeal. - For those out to REALLY maximize their money's worth, here's the trick. Order the quail or squab as an appetizer and an additional meat course as your entree. Mr. Danko is already generous with his portions, but apparantly he doesn't feel it's worth it to portion down the squab/quail dish so you get the whole damn bird! If you pull this stunt and go for the 5-course meal deal, you WILL be STUFFED!!! - For you cheese lovers out there, act REALLY excited when the cheese cart comes around. Technically, you're supposed to get 3 or 4 selections. But if you look like you're going to have an orgasm when the cheese hits your plate, your server will likely take pity on you and offer even more selections. - Whine, moan, and bitch like there's no tomorrow for an extra muffin at the end of your meal. As regulars know, Mr. Danko only offers the take-home muffin for the ladies at the table. Now we haven't tried the whining tactic yet, but we assume it'll work because no one wants to create a scene at Gary Danko's. *Last mystery to ponder: What happens when 2 guys dine together? Do they both get muffins? We may never know... -

I came here with my best friend (who was celebrating her birthday) and hubby to tantalize our taste buds. Dinner reservations were pretty late (9:30) on a weeknight and when we arrived it was still packed! We were warmly greeted and seated immediately. * Space: Warm, beautiful and incredibly well decorated. There was plenty of room in-between tables to maneuver around with winter coats. Also, the was perfectly sized for all of our dishes and table settings. * Atmosphere: Mood lighting was perfect. As romantic as the place looked at felt, it was fairly loud but not enough where you had to scream to be heard by the company you were with. The attire was nice casual to business dress - a wide range. * Drink: n/a - I only got still water so can't comment. * Eat: Every plate placed in front of us was presented so nicely. the seared sea scallops - melted in my mouth. Quail stuffed foie gros - deliciously filling. Seared beef filet - tender and juicy! I also tried the lobster risotto, which was divinely rich and flavorful. We got the baked chocolate soufflé with two sauces for dessert and a birthday lemon cake for my friend. Both were incredible, but I really liked the light flavoring of the lemon cake. Also, at the end of the night my friend and I got a complimentary coffeecake that was nicely wrapped up. * Service: Impeccable. We were asked if we wanted our coats to be hung up upon arriving - classy touch. The waitstaff was extremely friendly and very attentive. Our water glasses were always filled. Overall: Although I loved the service, enjoyed the succulent flavored food, and would definitely like to come back on another special occasion, I've had other restaurant/dinner experiences that really blew me away.

yay--finally i can say i've eaten at gary danko. it's a foodie institution in san francisco, and i am ashamed it took me so long. ok, so here's the real deal. this place is good. it's really good. but... and i have to to be honest, every time i eat somewhere where my bill comes to $300 (which is not often mind you) i always think how i could have had an equally amazing dinner for $150. so why does GD stand apart? 1. you can say you've eaten here. and maybe people will have more respect for you. 2. they deep fried a farm egg. i mean, come on. how did they do that? 3. the service is outstanding. loved our waiter. 4. and the cheese cart. literally the favorite part of my meal. my GOD, the cheese! you can stop reading now if you're bored. you know what you need to know. i would go back just to sit at the bar, drink bubbles, have an appetizer and eat cheese. seriously, do that and you will leave happy. special props to my app, which aside from the deep fried egg had creamy polenta, trumpet mushrooms and pancetta. also, loved my branzini on nettle gnocchi--quell yum. i actually think their apps are better than their entrees, but i have only tried 2 and at that point, was getting full. i consider myself a big eater, but i did not need to do 4 courses--they are larger than you would think--and i woulda been fine with 3. as far as mains, the duck was only ok for me--the carrot puree it came with reminded me of baby food. but the husband's pork belly was much, much better than mine and i was a lil jealous. we had the chocolate souffle for dessert, which was underwhelming after the cheese course. just finish with the cheese. trust me. trust me.

    10/26/2006

    In a nutshell:
    Decorative decor, warm ambiance, helpful and professional staff, and, oh yes, great food!

    In detail:
    Let's just go straight for the food, shall we? Everyone at my table ordered 5 courses, so of course, I did as well. 5 courses for $89...that's a "bargain!" But hey, you only live once. Anyway, yes, the food. If I can recall, here's what I ordered:

    Lobster Salad with Summer Melons
    Sweet White Corn Soup with Corn Truffle Ravioli
    Pancetta Wrapped Frog Legs
    Guinea Hen Breast and Boudin with Saffron Paella Rice, Chorizo, and Clam Ragout
    Baked Chocolate Souffle with Two Sauces

    The lobster salad was excellent. The lobster pieces were meaty and mouth-watering, while the melons were a good compliment to the dish.
    The sweet corn soup was excellent as well. The waiter first brought out a soup bowl with nothing but the corn truffle ravioli in the middle of it. It made me wonder, "Ummm...I could've sworn I ordered soup and not one piece of ravioli." But then he whipped out a miniature pot and in that pot was the corn soup. He poured it over the ravioli and for me, the rest...was heaven.
    The pancetta ("bacon") wrapped frog legs were very tasty. Frog legs taste like chicken. Everyone knows that. But whenever you wrap something up in pancetta ("bacon"), it always tastes good...ALWAYS!
    The hen breast was a disappointment for me. It lacked flavor. The fatty skin tasted good, but everything else lacked punch. The rice was a bit mushy and the boudin (first time I've eaten it) was something I'd rather not eat again. This course was the only lowlight of the dinner for me.
    The chocolate souffle was decadent. The two sauces were creme en glaze sauce...and I forgot the other. My only complaint about the souffle was that my souffle was rather mushy in the middle, as if it wasn't baked thoroughly enough. I can lay blame on the sauces, but I'm not so sure if the sauces made my souffle mushy. When you eat souffles, you expect it to be fluffy all the way through.

    My dining experience here was phenomenal! Even though there were a couple of small things that I didn't enjoy quite as much, they didn't sway my decision enough to make me rate this place below 5 stars.

    12/4/2009

    I must confess - my meal on 12/1/09 at Gary Danko is - to date - the best meal of my life.  It has totally reset my conception of food and fine dining...and in many ways has raised the proverbial bar for me as far as my yelp reviews.

    There are already over a thousand glowing reviews of Chef Danko & his restaurant...so you don't need me to tell you it's good...and honestly I've struggled for 3 days just trying to conceive of the words that I would use to describe this experience and actually do it justice.

    This restaurant was highly recommended to us by a family member, and (to be honest) we were skeptical that any meal or dining experience could really justify this type of price tag.  Upon stepping into the restaurant - we were warmly greeted, whisked away to our cozy table, and our waiter made his way to us quickly with menus and other relevant info.  The man and I had done some research - so we had a good idea of what we wanted to try - and we were able to place our full order quickly.  I chose the Autumn Tasting Menu with wine pairings and the man had 4 courses with tailored wine pairing as well.  As the amuse bouche arrived and then our first glass of wine...we quickly began to see that we were in for more than simply a meal...more than just great service...we were in for a guided tour of our sense of taste...an introspective exploration of our palates.

    The skepticism quickly faded...

    One thing I cannot say enough about is my appetizer - the Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar, Salsify and Lettuce Cream.  These delectable oysters are haunting my every thought!  The glaze...the lettuce cream...so inappropriate - but my goodness I could have that as a cup of soup!  I've had oysters and fresh from the Gulf Coast...I'd always thought they were good but they were kind of something i could live without...I'm pretty sure that's changed.  This appetizer perfectly communicates to you the essence of oyster and why it is something you should never live without.

    I could write pages about every dish and wine, but I will spare you.  However, our stars for the night were the previous mentioned oysters, Risotto with Lobster, Quail Stuffed with Foie Gras, Mushrooms and Quinoa, Yams, Salsify and Pomegranate, cheese cart, and the Warm Louisiana Butter Cake with Caramelized Apples, Huckleberry Compote and Vanilla Ice Cream.  Our review research led us to these choices, and we're so glad it did!!  

    Rounding out our other choices: Horseradish Crusted Salmon Medallion with Dilled Cucumbers and Mustard Sauce, Coconut Thai Curry with Lemongrass, Calamari, Lobster, Scallions and Shitake Mushrooms (wow the most tender and perfectly cooked calamari I've ever tasted), Seared Filet of Beef with Spaetzle, Butternut Squash, Crimini Mushrooms, Bone Marrow Butter and Shallot Marmalade (wow bone marrow butter and shallot marmalade - again delicious), Baked Chocolate Soufflé with Two Sauces.  All of these dishes were fantastic and shined in their own right.

    As I have mentioned in other reviews, I notice the little details when it comes to service.  Let me tell you - the service at this restaurant is on a whole other level.  These folks are so on top of their game and observant - you could almost swear that they read minds.  You never seem to be waiting or wanting for anything...you are either being given the perfect amount of info on your next wine...having your just finished dish whisked away...having your water refilled and you didn't even notice...and before you even knew you were waiting on your next course it's there and the joy of taste starts all over again.  We asked our waiter about mid meal if he could write down the man's wine pairings so we could reference them later.  Our waiter graciously did this for us AND included a copy of the Tasting Menu which he had Chef Danko sign for us.  This was waiting for us at the maître d' stand on beautiful restaurant stationary tucked away in a lovely gold envelope.  This was the perfect souvenir for our honeymoon trip to San Francisco and our visit to Gary Danko.

    Our final resolution is not only that the price is beyond fair for the meal and the experience...but that it's a MUST DO.  Maybe some budgets cannot allow every week, but it is definitely a must do at least once and as often as you can.

    10/7/2007

    This place is totally worth calling them 2 months ahead (to the day!) for my hubby's bday dinner.  I swear, my only regret of the night is that we should have gone here instead of Masa's for our anniversary a couple months ago.  Their 5 courses was was far superior to Masa's 9-course experience - The food tasted better (some orgasmic moments), their servings were much larger (I was super-stuffed at the end of the 5 courses, while still hungry at the end of the 9 courses), the wine pours more generous, and the service impeccable.

    Since I was driving, I let my hubby have the wine pairing (after all, it was his day), while I just ordered wine by the glass.

    Amuse-bouche - creamy green soup (I think the server said zucchini?).  Very warm and yummy, perfect thing to get us started.  We both got glasses of champagne which were just perfectly chilled, crisp, and dry.

    1st course - I got the Glazed Oysters w/ Osetra caviar, and man they really don't skimp on the caviar!  And this is considering they charge $95/ounce for it if you order the caviar service.  Tasted heavenly, a great start for the night.  Hubby got a nice-sized portion of seared foie gras (unlike some restaurants that give you a little tiny sliver).  I was still drinking my champagne while hubby got a sweet dessert wine (Tokai).  

    2nd course - I got the foie gras...this time an even larger portion than what my hubby got for his first course (mwahahahha!) since I got it as an entree (why get fish when you can get foie gras!).  If I wasn't set on trying some of the oysters w/ caviar I might have gotten 2 courses of this stuff, it's sooo damn good! :)  Hubby got seared sea scallops...it was super-good, just so buttery and perfectly cooked...prob the best sea scallops I've ever had (and I don't normally eat the stuff).  I'll still take my super-sized portion of foie gras over it though.  A nice light white wine came w/ my hubby's scallops, while I still extended my champagne from the beginning and finished off the last couple sips of my hubby's (hey, he got the full pairing anyway).  

    3rd course - I got quail stuffed w/ foie gras (can you tell I was craving foie gras?).  It was great, but my prize for best preparation of quail (or any poultry for that matter) still goes to Fleur de Lys for their quail stuffed w/ veal sweetbreads.  They give a much bigger portion here though  I still thought it was very good, better than my hubby's beef tenderloin...I think in the future, we should prob just avoid steaks at french restaurants, since you an get good steaks anyway, but the quail I got can only be gotten at fancy french places.  Since I asked them to pick my glass of wine for me, they gave me a nice light-to-medium bodied spanish rioja.  The server overpoured a little bit, and she was like "oops" and smiled at me.  I saw there was a little bit left over and the bottle and asked her if she can let me have it and she let me (yay!) and joked to not tell her boss. Hubby's wine pairing (a big heavy red for his steak) looked teeny tiny compared to my supersized serving of wine!  Whee!

    Cheese course - I gotta say, the cheese cart was extremely impressive.  I only wish I wasn't already kinda stuffed from the previous courses, then maybe I would have enjoyed it more.  All the cheeses I got (even the stinky ones) were excellent.  Hubby got this strong red wine that seemed very port-like in strength, but none of the sweetness...went really well w/ all the cheeses.  I'm still grateful for my extra-large pour for my quail so I actually still had wine left over for my cheese course!  Yay!

    Dessert - I got the chocolate souffle, hubby got grand marnier souffle.  They were both yummy, and again, a much larger portion than what I expected for a 5-course meal.  The server (different one this time) started pouring my hubby's wine pairing and saying it would go great w/ his chocolate souffle, but then I said that my hubby was actually getting the grand marnier.  He shrugged and said playfully that maybe he should just drink it, then gave it to me since I was getting the chocolate.  More free booze!  I'm loving this place.  Good thing it took us over 3 hours to eat so I can digest all the freebie alcohol :)

    After dessert, my hubby got a nice plate w/ a bunch of candies/goodies on it and it said happy birthday and had a candle.  We were so stuffed at this point, but I couldn't resist a few bites of the goodies! :)  I first told them about this a couple months ago so they had great attention to detail.  The service was also just so warm and friendly, which was very different from other restaurants of this caliber.  At the Ritz, they treated us like royalty, at Gary Danko, they treated us like their best friend.

    I gotta say this definitely one of the top meals I've had in the city...sure, I've had more spectacular meals, but those cost way more $$$!  Especially since this place is more affordable (esp if you get a 3-course), I will definitely come back!

    Hands down, our favorite restaurant in the city.  Ain't much more to add about the food so we'll spare the gory details.  We'd just like to inform all of you in Yelp-land of the subtler details of Mr. Danko's fine establishment:
    - The paradox of Danko, it's a great value considering it's high-end cuisine.  You ain't gonna find a much better deal for a multi-course meal with this level of service, ambience, and snob-appeal.
    - For those out to REALLY maximize their money's worth, here's the trick.  Order the quail or squab as an appetizer and an additional meat course as your entree.  Mr. Danko is already generous with his portions, but apparantly he doesn't feel it's worth it to portion down the squab/quail dish so you get the whole damn bird!  If you pull this stunt and go for the 5-course meal deal, you WILL be STUFFED!!!
    - For you cheese lovers out there, act REALLY excited when the cheese cart comes around.  Technically, you're supposed to get 3 or 4 selections.  But if you look like you're going to have an orgasm when the cheese hits your plate, your server will likely take pity on you and offer even more selections.
    - Whine, moan, and bitch like there's no tomorrow for an extra muffin at the end of your meal.  As regulars know, Mr. Danko only offers the take-home muffin for the ladies at the table.  Now we haven't tried the whining tactic yet, but we assume it'll work because no one wants to create a scene at Gary Danko's.

    *Last mystery to ponder:  What happens when 2 guys dine together?  Do they both get muffins?
    We may never know...
